27. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 639822460
T1  - Anti-Mullerian Hormone and Leutinising Hormone to Follicle Stimulating Hormone Ratio in the Diagnosis of Adolescent Girls with Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome
T3  - Annual Scientific Meeting of the Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, RANZCOG 2022. Gold Coast, QLD Australia.
A1  - Evans A.
A1  - Pankhurst M.
A1  - Evans K.
A1  - Pena A. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Introduction: Adolescent polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) is diagnosed using irregular menstrual cycles (relative to years post-menarche) and hyperandrogenism, according to international guidelines.1 Anti-Mullerian hormone (AMH) and leutinising hormone (LH)/follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) ratio are elevated in women with PCOS. However, AMH, pro-AMH and LH/FSH ratio are not currently used to diagnose PCOS. Aim(s): To identify if AMH, pro-AMH and LH/FSH ratio are useful in the diagnosis of PCOS in adolescents using recent guidelines.1 Methods: This study is a prospective cross-sectional study of adolescents with PCOS1 recruited from paediatric and gynaecology clinics. Participants had AMH, pro-AMH, LH, FSH, testosterone and sex hormone binding globulin (SHBG) measured. Result(s): Forty-one adolescents with PCOS (mean age 16.58 +/- 1.37 years, mean body mass index 31.41 +/- 9.06 kg/m2) had a mean AMH [interquartile range] of 59.26 pmol/L [28.98 to 73.92], mean pro-AMH of 21.80 pmol/L [17.15-27.13] and mean LH/FSH ratio of 2.21 +/- 1.65. Mean LH/FSH ratio was significantly greater than 1.23 (p = 0.0004) with 95% confidence intervals of 1.76 and infinity. 31/41 girls (76%) had an LH/FSH ratio > 1. LH/FSH ratio > 1 was significantly related to lower SHBG (r = 0.2, p = 0.01). Discussion(s): PCOS is difficult to diagnose in adolescence due to an overlap of physiological events during puberty. AMH, pro-AMH levels and LH/FSH ratio could be used to improve the diagnostic accuracy of PCOS in adolescent girls.
