53. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634417832
T1  - Testosterone reduction is differently related to insulin sensitivity in low vs. high FAI in PCOS
T3  - 38th Annual Meeting of the Obesity Society at Obesityweek. Virtual.
A1  - Tucker S.
A1  - Gower B.
A1  - Piccinini F.
A1  - Goss A. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Background: Women with PCOS have insulin resistance (IR) related to impaired insulin signaling in the muscle. Resulting hyperinsulinemia stimulates androgen production, contributing to many of the characteristic features of PCOS. The relationships between changes in testosterone with improvements in hepatic, muscular, and whole-body IR have not been explored. We aim to test the hypothesis that improvements in testosterone are associated with improvements in muscle specific (the oral minimal model (OMM)) and whole-body (Matsuda equation) measures of insulin sensitivity (IS) but not a liver specific measure (HOMA-IR) among women with PCOS with high and low hyperandrogenism measured by the free androgen index (FAI). Method(s): Thirty women with PCOS were provided two diets differing in glycemic load for 8-weeks in random order. Before and after each diet arm, a liquid meal tolerance test was used to determine measures of IR/IS. FAI was split into two categories based on the median and used to compare high and low hyperandrogenism. Result(s): Women with high FAI compared to low FAI were not different in baseline measures of IR and IS, fat mass, or lean mass. After adjustment for diet, increases in the OMM were related to decreases in testosterone (R = -4.41, p = 0.01), and remained significant after further adjustment for changes in total body fat within the low FAI group. Contrarily in the high FAI group, reduced testosterone was associated with increases in Matsuda (R = -8.57, p = 0.06) and decreases in HOMA-IR (R = 13.79, p = 0.03), however these associations were not significant after adjustment for change in total body fat. Conclusion(s): Among women with PCOS, improvement in skeletal muscle IS is related to improvements in testosterone within women with a low FAI. However, in women with a high FAI, improvements in hepatic and whole-body IR are related to improvements in testosterone, but this relationship is influenced by fat loss.
