T1  - Free androgen index may be the most useful biochemical androgenic marker for the detection of PCOS
T3  - 22nd FIGO World Congress of Gynecology and Obstetrics. Rio de Janeiro Brazil.
A1  - Kim J.
A1  - Hwang K.R.
A1  - Kim B.J.
A1  - Park J.S.
A1  - Choi Y.M. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Objectives: Hyperandrogenism is a diagnostic criteria for polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). The purpose of this study was to investigate the diagnostic performance of androgens for the detection of PCOS. Method(s): This was a tertiary university hospital based case control study. The covariate adjusted receiver operating characteristic (ROC) curve analyses of androgens were performed for 250 women with PCOS and 89 controls. The Rotterdam criteria was used, but biochemical hyperandrogenism was not included for the diagnosis of PCOS. Main outcome measures were area under the curves (AUCs) of different serum androgen parameters. Result(s): The highest AUC was that of free androgen index (FAI) [0.808 (95% confidence intervals 0.764-0.853) in age-adjusted model and 0.715 (95% confidence intervals 0.644-0.785) in age and BMI-adjusted model], which was significantly higher than those of total testosterone (T), bioavailable T and calculated free T after Bonferroni corrections. The suggested decision thresholds of FAI for the detection of PCOS was 2.06 (sensitivity 72.8% and specificity 78.6%) in age-adjusted model and 2.38 (sensitivity 58.8% and specificity 76.5%) in age and BMI-adjusted ROC models. Conclusion(s): Our findings suggest that FAI might be the most useful biochemical hyperandrogenism parameter for the detection of PCOS.
